Well, first things first, know the scale of your work. That way you don't try to shove the explanation of a political system, a religion, and four cultures into something less than 10k words in length. If you have to ask how to write a story, then you sure as hell don't need to be shooting for novel length. Get some short stories under your belt before you even dream of approaching an editor, let alone a goddamn publisher.

Keep it succinct; my two long pieces (Tough to Love and Lightning in a Bottle) were purposely aimed to finish at 11kish words, which is one of Wikipedia's word count requirements to be considered novellas. That way I have a goal to shoot for when I do something substantial instead of just churn out an update (Femme Fatal, by the way, has passed some 21k total words according to WPS Writer), but it helps me approach it seriously while also keeping myself grounded in my capabilities. Fun fact: I'm not writing expert beyond my experience as a college tutor and having RPed for years; /hmofa/ has seen literally all of my written material because it's the only thing I've done. I have a 'serious' non-smut story that's a couple pages in, but writing /hmofa/ stuff is usually more fun.

Right, so you have sanded your expectations down and reminded yourself you're not the next Stephen King or J.K. Rowling. Short stories are perfectly fine to go for, but force you to realize that you can't just spew words upon words like a torrent of information; raw info dumps are a cardinal sin in writing. So if you want to world build and bring the reader into the know about the goings on of the setting, you have to do so in passing as the story progresses.

Cont)

>>10864506
The thing that will make sure you actually write your story is having the story already planned out, at least a little. You remember the outlines you made for highschool and college assignments? Yeah, you could use the same method if it helps.

Have the entire concept of the story you want to tell already written out. And then, add a beginning, middle, and end. Or, and end, beginning, and middle. You can mix and match these; Lightning in the Bottle was basically written backwards from how I wanted it to end (dude handcuffed to a bed at the mercy of an enthusiastic rat) and then figuring out how things got that way.

So you know how things are going to go ahead of time when you start writing; point A, B, and C are marked, and you just have to hustle between them. This removes the "so, hmmm, where do I go next from here?" because you already know what should come next, AND since it's a short story you don't time to dilly dally about it. Now you can settle in and get to writing.

Eventually you bang out your story, and you get to the true final boss of writing; review, editing, and rewriting. Repeat after me, because if you ignore this you'll regret it: No first draft is the final draft. You hit that finally punctuation mark take a well deserved break, but you have to come back and put in some time with a hatchet and a polish rag.

Is there a part that feels a bit bland and could survive an injection of a paragraph or three? Did you go overboard on another part and realize things are getting dry? Rewrite, rewrite, rewrite. Check your word usage, make sure you're keeping in the same tense. The story has been written, but the elbow grease comes out while you're editing. You may want to employ a friend or two to read over what you have, just in case they see problems that you're glossing over.

When you finally can't get anymore shine out of your piece (or you cannot be fucked to go another round of editing), go ahead and let it out into the wild.
